<TITLE> House opens probe into BNP govt 'irregularities' </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 04 (bdnews24.com)A parliamentary watchdog has formed a five-member committee to inquire into the alleged irregularities that took place in the social welfare department during rule of the BNP-led alliance. The parliamentary standing committee on social welfare ministry on Sunday constituted the committee headed by ruling Awami League MP Monirul Islam, according to the paper on the decision of the committee. Chemon Ara Begum, Jebun Nessa, Mahjabin Morshed and Md Jasim Uddin are the other members of the sub-committee, said the paper. However, the meeting did not mention any specific allegations committed from 2001 to 2006 when the main opposition BNP was in power. The meeting sources said ruling Awami League MP Chemon Ara Begum raised the issue at the meeting and proposed formation of the body. She said the probe should also investigate the appointment and promotion of public servants during the BNP's tenure. As per the paper presented to the meeting by the social welfare ministry, 556 public servants got appointment from 2001 to 2008. Of them, 190 were class one while 38 second class officers. As many as 203 class three and 119 class four employees were appointed during the time that includes rules of the BNP and the immediate-past military-installed caretaker government. Again, six staff were appointed with consolidated payment. The committee chairman Md Mozammel Hossain presided over the meeting.
